{"cursor":"3389","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox President\n| name='Roberto M. Ortiz' image= Robertomortiz.jpg imagesize=210px\n| nationality=Argentine order=President of Argentina term_start=February 20,\n| 1938 term_end=June 26, 1942 predecessor=AgustÃ­n P. Justo successor=RamÃ³n\n| Castillo birth_date= birth_place= Buenos Aires death_date= death_place= Buenos\n| Aires spouse= party=Concordancia (UCR-A, PSI, PDN) vicepresident= RamÃ³n\n| Castillo profession=Lawyer\n}}\n\n'Jaime Gerardo Roberto Marcelino MarÃ­a Ortiz Lizardi' (September 24, 1886\n– July 15, 1942) was President of Argentina from February 20, 1938 to\nJune 27, 1942.\n\nOrtiz was born in Buenos Aires. As a student at the University of Buenos Aires,\nhe participated in an unsuccessful revolution in 1905. In 1909 he graduated from\nthe university and became a lawyer.\n\nHe became active in the Radical Civic Union and was elected to the Argentine\nNational Congress in 1920. He served as minister of public works from 1925 to\n1928. He supported the revolution of 1930 and served as treasury minister from\n1935 to 1937.\n\nIn the presidential elections of 1937, he was the official government candidate\nand won, though the opposition accused him of participating in fraud, as\nirregularities were widespread. Ortiz never denied those charges but once he\ntook office he tried to make Argentine politics more open and truly democratic.\nSoon after becoming president, Ortiz became seriously ill with diabetes and in\nAugust 1940, he gave up his powers to vice-president RamÃ³n Castillo. He was pro-\nAlly but because of opposition in the army, he didn't break relations with the\nAxis. He resigned a few weeks before his death.\n","linknr":252,"url":"Roberto_María_Ortiz","recorded":1375087231,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Roberto_Mar%C3%ADa_Ortiz&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Roberto_Mar%C3%ADa_Ortiz&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","/